ife histories but exploring mentalities as well as experiences, against a setting of deep social and economic change. Key moments are the 1970s loss of Britons’ privilege in Commonwealth destination countries, ‘Thatcher’s refugees’ in the 1980s and shifting attitudes to cosmopolitanism and global citizenship by the 1990s. It charts a long process of change from the 1960s to patterns of discretionary and nomadic migration, which became more common practice from the end of the twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBritishxSocial conditionsxForeign countries. 0aBritishzForeign countriesxSocial conditions. 0aGreat BritainxEmigration and immigration. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aBritish diaspora.  aBritish emigrants.  aCommonwealth countries.  aThatcher's refugees.  aausterity.  acosmopolitanism.  aemigration resurgence.  alifestyle migration.  amigrant careers.  amigrant experiences.  amigration patterns.  amodern migration.  amodern mobility.  anomadic migration.  anon-white migration.  apostwar migration.  aprivate life.  areturn experiences.  atreechange phenomenon.  awhite settlement.1 aHammerton, A. James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packagez978311128281740uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152611658140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526116581423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526116581/original  a978-3-11-128281-7  Manchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packageb2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles